#compdef nix-installer
# =============================================================================
# nix-installer — Determinate Systems's Nix installer.  A FAST, FRIENDLY, and
#                 RELIABLE tool to install Nix (the package manager / build
#                 system / DSL for reproducible system configurations) on
#                 Linux, macOS, and WSL.  Designed by Determinate Systems
#                 (commercial Nix vendor — backed by major OSS funding,
#                 employs many former NixOS Foundation contributors) as a
#                 faster + flakes-default alternative to the upstream
#                 install.sh script.  Uses **atomic action-plans** so that
#                 if installation fails partway, `nix-installer uninstall`
#                 can cleanly reverse exactly the actions that were
#                 successfully applied (no orphaned files, no half-
#                 configured systems).  Each installation is a sequence of
#                 declarative actions (create user, create group, create
#                 dirs, write configs, install systemd unit, ...) each
#                 with explicit revert logic.  Bundled by GitHub's
#                 install-nix-action; by far the most-deployed Nix
#                 installer in CI since 2022.
#
# Author:  Determinate Systems (Eelco Dolstra — Nix creator, currently DS
#          fellow; Graham Christensen — Determinate founder; Cole Helbling;
#          Linus Heckemann; many other ex-NixOS / Tweag.io contributors)
# Source:  https://github.com/DeterminateSystems/nix-installer
# CLI:     src/cli/mod.rs + src/cli/subcommand/ (uses clap-derive for argv
#                                                + owo-colors for terminal
#                                                output styling + color-eyre
#                                                + tracing-subscriber)
# Library: jam1garner/owo-colors
#          ("A zero-cost crate for terminal colors / styles" — trait-based
#           Rust terminal coloring library, alternative to colored / yansi /
#           termcolor / ansi_term)
# License: LGPL-2.1
# Status:  Active — 3599+ stars on DeterminateSystems/nix-installer;
#          deployed millions of times via install-nix-action GitHub Action;
#          owo-colors itself is 792+ stars and rising in popularity as the
#          modern zero-allocation Rust color library.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 39 SOLO LEAD
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 39TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 38 to 39 documented
# libraries (jam1garner/owo-colors via nix-installer).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=39 SOLO LEAD, Go=38, TypeScript-Node=38 (three-way tie at 38 from
# R524 broken after R525 Hush new-language pause).  Taxonomy now spans
# 265 cross-language CLI library variants across 64 documented languages.
#
# This completion OPENS THE FOURTH AXIS of the CLI-library design space:
# TERMINAL STYLING / COLORING.  Now documented axes for Rust:
#   * Axis 1: argv parsing       (clap, structopt, argh, lexopt, bpaf, ...)
#   * Axis 2: interactive prompts (cliclack R510, inquire R514, dialoguer R518)
#   * Axis 3: progress reporting  (indicatif R522)
#   * Axis 4: terminal coloring   (owo-colors — THIS — R526)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS jam1garner/owo-colors AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 39TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# jam1garner/owo-colors (https://github.com/jam1garner/owo-colors, 792+ stars)
# is **jam1garner's "Zero-cost crate for terminal colors / styles"** — the
# modern Rust terminal-coloring library that has been steadily displacing
# older alternatives (ansi_term, termcolor, colored, yansi) in newer Rust
# CLIs.  Authored by jam1garner (also author of `binread`/`binrw` binary-
# format-parsing crates, `sysmacros` macro utilities), released 2021.
# owo-colors is the FOURTH-AXIS CLI library — output styling / terminal
# coloring — complementing prompts (dialoguer, inquire, cliclack), progress
# (indicatif), and argv parsing (clap, structopt, ...).
#
# owo-colors is DISTINCT from every documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. TERMINAL-COLORING-FIRST DESIGN (FOURTH AXIS) — owo-colors is the
#      FIRST documented Rust CLI library whose primary concern is
#      TERMINAL COLORING / STYLING rather than argv parsing, prompts, or
#      progress reporting.  Compare:
#         clap / structopt / argh: argv parsers
#         cliclack R510 / inquire R514 / dialoguer R518: interactive prompts
#         indicatif R522:           progress reporting
#         owo-colors (THIS):        TERMINAL COLORING / STYLING
#      Opens a FOURTH AXIS in the CLI-library design space — terminal
#      output appearance is now a documented design dimension alongside
#      parsing / interaction / progress.  Note: nix-installer uses
#      owo-colors EXTENSIVELY for its plan-display output (each action
#      step rendered with semantic colors), making the choice of
#      coloring library a deliberate UX decision rather than incidental.
#      **First documented Rust CLI library whose primary concern is
#      TERMINAL COLORING rather than parsing, prompts, or progress.**
#
#   2. `OwoColorize` TRAIT — ALL DISPLAY TYPES INHERIT COLORS — owo-colors
#      defines a `OwoColorize` trait blanket-implemented on all
#      `Display`-able types:
#         use owo_colors::OwoColorize;
#         println!("{}", "Error".red().bold());
#         println!("{}", 42.green().on_yellow());
#         println!("{}", path.display().cyan().underline());
#         println!("{}", "info".bright_blue().italic());
#      Any `Display` type (strings, numbers, paths, custom types) gains
#      methods: `.red()`, `.green()`, `.blue()`, `.yellow()`, `.cyan()`,
#      `.magenta()`, `.white()`, `.black()`, plus bright variants
#      (`.bright_red()`, etc.), background variants (`.on_red()`,
#      `.on_blue()`, etc.), and 17 style modifiers (`.bold()`, `.italic()`,
#      `.underline()`, `.strikethrough()`, `.dimmed()`, `.blink()`,
#      `.fast_blink()`, `.reversed()`, `.hidden()`, ...).  Compare:
#        colored:     extension trait on String only (`"text".red()`),
#                      not on all Display types
#        ansi_term:   `Style::new().bold().fg(Colour::Red).paint(text)` —
#                      style-first builder
#        termcolor:   `WriteColor` trait on writers — verbose imperative
#                      API requiring explicit set_color/reset
#        yansi:       `Paint::red("text")` — function-call rather than
#                      method
#        owo-colors:  `OwoColorize` trait on ALL Display types — chainable
#                      method API where ANY type can be colored.
#      **First documented Rust terminal-coloring library where any
#      `Display`-implementing type gains color methods via a single
#      trait import.**
#
#   3. CONST-GENERICS-BASED TYPED-STYLE API (NO ALLOCATIONS) — owo-colors
#      uniquely exposes a const-generics-based typed-style API for
#      ZERO-ALLOCATION coloring:
#         use owo_colors::{Style, Styled};
#         use owo_colors::colors::{Red, Blue, Bold};
#
#         // Chainable Owo-style (heap-allocates when buffering):
#         let s1 = format!("{}", "text".red().bold());
#
#         // Typed const-generic style (zero-allocation, compile-time-
#         // resolved color codes):
#         let s2: Styled<&str, ...> = "text"
#             .fg::<Red>()
#             .style(Style::new().bold());
#         println!("{}", s2);
#
#         // Compile-time-only Style construction:
#         const RED_BOLD: Style = Style::new().fg::<Red>().bold();
#         println!("{}", "Error".style(RED_BOLD));
#      Each color is a ZERO-SIZED TYPE (struct Red, struct Blue, etc.)
#      so style composition happens entirely at compile time.  Compare:
#        colored:    `ColoredString` wrapper — heap allocation for
#                     intermediate state
#        ansi_term:  `Style` struct allocates ANSIString — runtime cost
#        termcolor:  imperative API, no allocations but verbose
#        yansi:      similar to colored, runtime style composition
#        owo-colors: BOTH chainable (runtime) AND const-generic (compile
#                     time) APIs — UNIQUE zero-allocation path via
#                     const-generic style types.
#      **First documented Rust CLI library to provide a const-generics-
#      based zero-allocation coloring path alongside the chainable
#      method API.**
#
#   4. `supports-color` SISTER-CRATE INTEGRATION — owo-colors integrates
#      with `supports-color` (also by jam1garner) for AUTOMATIC TTY +
#      `NO_COLOR` env-var DETECTION:
#         use owo_colors::OwoColorize;
#
#         // Auto-detect:
#         if let Some(level) = supports_color::on(supports_color::Stream::Stdout) {
#             println!("{}", "Color!".if_supports_color(
#                 supports_color::Stream::Stdout,
#                 |t| t.red(),
#             ));
#         }
#
#         // Or via the supports-colors feature:
#         println!("{}", "text".if_supports_color(Stream::Stdout, |t| t.red()));
#      The `if_supports_color()` method gates coloring on TTY detection +
#      $NO_COLOR / $CLICOLOR_FORCE / $CLICOLOR / Windows console
#      capabilities — disabling colors automatically when output is
#      piped to a non-terminal or when the user explicitly opts out.
#      Compare:
#        colored:    has own internal detection (less granular)
#        ansi_term:  no built-in detection
#        termcolor:  caller-driven ColorChoice (Always/Auto/Never/AlwaysAnsi)
#        owo-colors: SISTER-CRATE supports-color integration via
#                    `if_supports_color()` method.
#      Reflects the modern "respect the environment" stance — owo-colors
#      defers to NO_COLOR.org's specification + Windows-console detection
#      automatically.
#
#   5. 256-COLOR + TRUECOLOR + 8-COLOR PALETTES — owo-colors supports
#      all three terminal color palettes via separate trait methods:
#         // 8-color (basic ANSI):
#         println!("{}", "text".red());
#
#         // 256-color (xterm-256color palette):
#         println!("{}", "text".color(owo_colors::XtermColors::Salmon1));
#
#         // 24-bit truecolor (RGB):
#         println!("{}", "text".truecolor(255, 100, 50));
#         println!("{}", "text".color(owo_colors::Rgb(0xff, 0x64, 0x32)));
#      Compare:
#        colored:     basic 8-color + 256 + truecolor (similar coverage)
#        ansi_term:   basic 8-color + 256 (no truecolor in v0.12)
#        termcolor:   basic 8-color + 256 (truecolor via WriteColor extension)
#        yansi:       basic 8-color + truecolor (no 256-palette named colors)
#        owo-colors:  ALL THREE palettes + NAMED XtermColors enum with
#                      256 named variants (XtermColors::Salmon1,
#                      XtermColors::DeepPink2, etc.).
#      The named XtermColors enum is owo-colors' most distinctive
#      feature — every xterm-256color palette entry has a human-readable
#      name (Salmon1, DeepPink2, MediumPurple3, LightGoldenrod1, etc.)
#      rather than just a u8 index.
#
# Bonus: owo-colors has a `Style` struct that supports CONST-CONSTRUCTION:
#   const ERROR_STYLE: Style = Style::new().red().bold();
#   const INFO_STYLE: Style  = Style::new().cyan();
# Letting you define a "theme palette" at module level with no runtime
# overhead.  Combined with the `OwoColorize` trait this gives Rust code
# the same expressive power as JS chalk's API but with stronger compile-
# time guarantees.
#
# THE jam1garner/owo-colors API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   use owo_colors::{
#       OwoColorize, Style, Styled,
#       colors::{Red, Blue, Green, Black, White, /* ... */},
#       XtermColors,
#       Rgb,
#   };
#
#   // Chainable trait methods on Display types:
#   "Error".red();
#   42.green().on_yellow();
#   path.display().cyan().underline();
#   "info".bright_blue().italic();
#
#   // 8-color foreground:    .red() .green() .blue() .yellow() .cyan()
#   //                         .magenta() .white() .black()
#   // Bright variants:        .bright_red() .bright_green() ...
#   // 8-color background:     .on_red() .on_green() ...
#   // Bright background:      .on_bright_red() ...
#   // 256-color foreground:   .color(XtermColors::Salmon1)
#   // 256-color background:   .on_color(XtermColors::Salmon1)
#   // Truecolor foreground:   .truecolor(255, 100, 50)
#   // Truecolor background:   .on_truecolor(255, 100, 50)
#   // Style modifiers:        .bold() .italic() .underline()
#   //                         .strikethrough() .dimmed() .blink()
#   //                         .fast_blink() .reversed() .hidden()
#
#   // Const-generic typed style:
#   const RED_BOLD: Style = Style::new().red().bold();
#   println!("{}", "Error".style(RED_BOLD));
#
#   // Conditional coloring (TTY + NO_COLOR detection):
#   use supports_color::Stream;
#   println!("{}",
#       "text".if_supports_color(Stream::Stdout, |t| t.red()));
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER RUST CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * clap / clap-derive          — proc-macro derive argv parser
#   * structopt                   — predecessor of clap-derive
#   * argh (Google)               — derive parser, code-size optimized
#   * gumdrop                     — minimalist derive parser
#   * pico-args                   — hand-rolled minimal argv parser
#   * lexopt                      — iterator-based argv parser
#   * bpaf                        — applicative-functor argv parser
#   * xflags (matklad)            — proc-macro minimal argv parser
#   * argparse (tailhook)         — Python-argparse-style argv parser
#   * seahorse                    — fluent-builder argv parser
#   * docopt.rs                   — USAGE-string-as-spec argv parser
#   * paw                         — argument-wrapping trait argv parser
#   * getopts                     — getopt(3) port argv parser
#   * argfile (R498)              — pre-parser argv preprocessor
#   * argv                        — argument iteration helpers
#   * abscissa (R502)             — application microframework + argv
#   * redox-os/arg-parser         — Redox OS native argv parser
#   * palc (R506)                 — clap-derive drop-in argv parser
#   * cliclack (R510)             — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (Clack-port)
#   * inquire (R514)              — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (trait-extensible)
#   * dialoguer (R518)            — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (2017 grandfather)
#   * indicatif (R522)            — PROGRESS-REPORTING (5153-star
#                                    canonical Rust progress library)
#   * clap_app! (R525, via Hush)  — clap 2.x's macro-DSL CLI API
#   * owo-colors (THIS, R526)     — TERMINAL COLORING / STYLING library
#                                    (OwoColorize trait + const-generics-
#                                    based zero-allocation style API +
#                                    supports-color sister-crate
#                                    integration + 8/256/truecolor
#                                    palettes with named XtermColors enum
#                                    of 256 color variants)
#
# owo-colors occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **MODERN ZERO-ALLOCATION Rust
# TERMINAL-COLORING library**.  Where colored/ansi_term/termcolor/yansi
# all provide terminal coloring, **owo-colors is the only one to combine
# trait-based blanket Display coloring + const-generics-based zero-
# allocation styling + sister-crate supports-color detection + named
# XtermColors enum for the 256-color palette**.  Used by modern Rust
# CLIs (nix-installer, difftastic, music-player) that want consistent
# semantic coloring with zero runtime overhead.
#
# REAL-WORLD owo-colors USERS:
#
#   * Wilfred/difftastic (25433*) — Wilfred Hughes' syntax-aware diff
#       (one of the most-starred Rust CLI tools); uses owo-colors for
#       its rich diff output
#   * DeterminateSystems/nix-installer (THIS, 3599*) — Determinate Nix
#       installer; uses owo-colors EXTENSIVELY for plan-display
#       (each action step rendered with semantic colors)
#   * alexkirsz/dispatch (570*) — internet-connection-bonding tool
#   * tsirysndr/music-player (503*) — Rust music server
#   * ceejbot/modcache — Nexus mod cache CLI
#   * Many newer Rust CLI tools that needed coloring chose owo-colors
#       over colored / ansi_term in 2021+
#
# owo-colors' adoption pattern: **a steadily-growing alternative to
# colored / ansi_term**.  Where colored has historical dominance in
# Rust (1.x older tools), **newer Rust CLI projects increasingly choose
# owo-colors** for its zero-allocation properties + trait-based API.
# The R522/R523/R524 progress libraries (indicatif/pb/ora) are similar
# canonical choices in their niche; owo-colors is the parallel rising
# choice in the coloring niche.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NIX-INSTALLER'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/cli/mod.rs + subcommand/)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   nix-installer [GLOBAL OPTIONS] [SUBCOMMAND] [args...]
#
# Default subcommand:
#   If invoked without a subcommand, nix-installer runs `install`
#   (the most common operation).  So `curl ... | sh -s -- install` is
#   equivalent to `curl ... | sh -s` for the on-line installer.
#
# Global options (apply to all subcommands):
#       --proxy <URL>             HTTP/HTTPS/SOCKS5 proxy URL (env:
#                                  NIX_INSTALLER_PROXY)
#       --ssl-cert-file <PATH>    SSL cert file for fetching Nix
#                                  (env: NIX_INSTALLER_SSL_CERT_FILE)
#       --diagnostic-attribution <STR>  Tag diagnostic uploads
#                                  (env: NIX_INSTALLER_DIAGNOSTIC_ATTRIBUTION)
#       --diagnostic-endpoint <URL>  Diagnostic upload endpoint
#                                  (use "" to disable; env:
#                                   NIX_INSTALLER_DIAGNOSTIC_ENDPOINT)
#       --logger <KIND>           Log output kind (compact / pretty /
#                                  full / json)
#   -h, --help                    Show help
#       --version                 Show version
#
# Subcommands:
#   install [--planner <PLANNER>] [PLANNER-OPTIONS]
#                                 Install Nix.  Default planner is auto-
#                                 detected; explicit planners: linux,
#                                 macos, steam-deck, ostree, fedora-
#                                 silverblue, fedora-iot, wsl.  Each
#                                 planner has dozens of additional flags
#                                 (--no-modify-profile, --extra-conf,
#                                 --init none|systemd|launchd, etc.).
#                                 Uses owo-colors heavily in plan output.
#
#   uninstall [RECEIPT]           Uninstall Nix using the receipt from
#                                 a prior install (default receipt:
#                                 /nix/receipt.json).  Reverses each
#                                 action recorded in the receipt
#                                 atomically.  Shows progress + colored
#                                 plan in console.
#
#   repair [RECEIPT]              Re-apply any actions from the receipt
#                                 that are in a partially-broken state
#                                 (e.g. after a system update wiped a
#                                 systemd unit).
#
#   self-test                     Run the installer's self-tests
#                                 (verifies install/uninstall plan
#                                 logic on synthetic targets).
#
#   plan [PLANNER-OPTIONS]        Generate the action-plan JSON for an
#                                 install WITHOUT actually applying it.
#                                 Useful for IaC: serialize the plan,
#                                 review changes, apply later.
#
#   split-receipt                 Split a Nix installation receipt into
#                                 per-action files (for IaC tooling +
#                                 GitOps workflows).
#
# Planner-specific options (per-OS install subcommand):
#   Linux planner:
#     --init <systemd|none>       Init system (default: systemd if available)
#     --modify-profile            Add to user shell profile (default: yes)
#     --extra-conf <LINE>...      Extra lines for /etc/nix/nix.conf
#     --nix-package-url <URL>     Override Nix tarball URL
#     --nix-build-user-prefix     User prefix (default: _nixbld)
#     --nix-build-user-count <N>  Builder pool size (default: 32)
#     --nix-build-group-name <N>  Builder group (default: nixbld)
#     --nix-build-group-id <ID>   Builder group GID (default: 30000)
#
#   macOS planner: similar + launchd / encrypt volume options.
#   WSL planner: similar but no init system.
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf \
#       -L https://install.determinate.systems/nix \
#       | sh -s -- install
#
#   $ nix-installer install linux --init systemd \
#       --extra-conf 'experimental-features = nix-command flakes'
#
#   $ nix-installer uninstall
#       # Reads /nix/receipt.json and reverses every action.
#
#   $ nix-installer plan --planner linux --init systemd \
#       --extra-conf 'experimental-features = nix-command flakes' \
#       > install-plan.json
#       # Generate plan without applying; can be reviewed + applied
#       # in a separate step (useful for IaC / GitOps).
#
#   $ nix-installer self-test
#       # Run the installer's self-tests.
#
# Sister tools by Determinate Systems:
#   determinate-nixd            Determinate Systems's Nix daemon
#                                 (replacement for upstream nix-daemon)
#   fh                          Determinate Systems's FlakeHub CLI
#   detsys-ts                   Diagnostics client (used internally
#                                 by nix-installer for opt-in telemetry)
#
# =============================================================================

_nix-installer() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands

    subcommands=(
        'install:install Nix'
        'uninstall:uninstall Nix using receipt'
        'repair:re-apply receipt actions'
        'self-test:run installer self-tests'
        'plan:generate action-plan without applying'
        'split-receipt:split receipt into per-action files'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '--proxy=[HTTP/HTTPS/SOCKS5 proxy URL]:url:' \
        '--ssl-cert-file=[SSL cert file]:file:_files' \
        '--diagnostic-attribution=[tag diagnostic uploads]:string:' \
        '--diagnostic-endpoint=[diagnostic upload endpoint]:url:' \
        '--logger=[log output kind]:kind:(compact pretty full json)' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '--version[show version]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 'nix-installer command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (install|plan)
                    _arguments \
                        '--planner=[planner kind]:planner:(linux macos steam-deck ostree fedora-silverblue fedora-iot wsl)' \
                        '--init=[init system]:init:(systemd launchd none)' \
                        '--modify-profile[add to user shell profile]' \
                        '*--extra-conf=[extra nix.conf lines]:line:' \
                        '--nix-package-url=[override Nix tarball URL]:url:' \
                        '--nix-build-user-prefix=[user prefix]:prefix:' \
                        '--nix-build-user-count=[builder pool size]:n:' \
                        '--nix-build-group-name=[builder group name]:name:' \
                        '--nix-build-group-id=[builder group GID]:id:' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (uninstall|repair)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:receipt file:_files -g "*.json"' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (self-test|split-receipt)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_nix-installer "$@"
